,Not Recommended,209670,28749505,"Posted: 28 December, 2016",all,Freefall1984,"It's rare that I'll say a game is terrible, but this game has the least intuitive UI in any title I've ever played, and that's enough to result in a terrible game. You have no warning when you're being attacked at the other side of the map, you have no way of knowing which weapon you have equipped unless you know the ammo quantities and which weapon ""model"" is which. The tutorial is a single level with a half a dozen sign posts to tell you how to play on a game with considerable depth as this, that is not enough. The floor seems to melt away as you're walking on it resulting in getting stuck in the floor. There is no progression to show you which weapons are better than other or which bodies are more capable than others. You get given a list of several hundred buyable items and get no indication on which ones are worth buying. The campaign is simply a series of skirmishes with a shared resource pool. The graphics are mediocre, looking almost as though the whole game and all the assets are developed to play in 640 X 480, aiming is terrible and unintuitive, sometimes working and sometimes not, can we have an Aim button so we know when we're aiming or otherwise. Why can I not see any range of distance when aiming, often having to approximate the thing I'm aiming at but I can somehow see anywhere on the map when I'm choosing my delivery locations?Personally I think the game would have had a lot of potential, but in it's current state it almost seems like the thing is having an identity crisis, it's like the game doesn't know if it want's to be a strategy game or a 2d action platformer. I think I would prefer it if it was played entirely like an RTS game and I could just pause the action issue commands to my troops where to move and which direction to cover etc. For a game which has been in development for such a long time, it seems that the developers have had no clear direction and rather than ending up with a solid game, have instead ended up with a digital identity crisis."
